WEBVTT

00:02.410 --> 00:09.663
Oldest business in Richmond, I believe, has been 
in business continuously. I think the oldest one

00:09.683 --> 00:12.248
here is a lumber yard. It wasn't an old lumber 
company.

00:18.420 --> 00:20.143
That's Joe Clyde Westendorf, right? Yeah, well, 
it started out, it was, Oh, I don't remember now

00:27.453 --> 00:50.855
what the old original Wessendorf was here in that 
lumber business, but his boy, Tony Wessendorf,

00:27.453 --> 00:50.855
T.B., they called him, he took over back, 
somewhere back in 1900 or so. He was operating it

00:50.875 --> 00:56.420
before I started school. And Joe was his nephew, 
wasn't he? Well, Joe's daddy, that's Joe Clyde's

01:01.734 --> 01:08.763
daddy, was his nephew, Tony's nephew. Then it was 
Joe Clyde. And Joe Clyde's granddaddy, who had an

01:14.149 --> 01:21.698
insurance business here since way back before I 
can remember. And Joe Clyde inherited that from

01:23.520 --> 01:27.885
his granddaddy. Now, the Wessendorffs were some 
of the original settlers of Richmond, right?

01:33.058 --> 01:36.563
Well, they were pretty well, they were well fixed. 
But there was, oh shucks, Bertrand, Winston,

01:38.365 --> 01:56.370
Bassett, and so on down the line that had just all 
kinds of land, cattle, and then farm cutting.

01:58.831 --> 02:13.329
As long as 1919, right after the First World War, 
cotton, the price of cotton just went way up, you

01:58.831 --> 02:13.329
know. They made a big crop there. Everybody had 
lots of money. But cotton has been the main

02:19.998 --> 02:24.684
agricultural crop. Well... Then you came along 
with oil. There was a mill here that sugarcane.

02:35.164 --> 02:44.379
Across the bridge, you know, where the old Bill 
Williams Cafe is out there. That big cafe just a

02:44.399 --> 02:51.931
little past it all the way to Sugar Land used to be 
solid sugarcane. And the Bertrand Farm sugarcane

02:51.951 --> 02:54.555
then. But when the sugar cane business got to where 
they couldn't get help, at that time, you could

02:55.750 --> 03:05.061
rent convicts from the state. You had to have a 
building to keep them in, and bars on the windows,

03:06.683 --> 03:13.631
and so forth, and guards. But you could rent 
convicts. I don't have any idea how cheap, but I

03:15.673 --> 03:25.605
know they could rent them cheap, because the cane 
farmers over there used them. I think cut that out.

03:31.169 --> 03:37.759
Eventually, Sugar Land quit crushing cane. See, 
these farmers and the state, the state prison

03:38.941 --> 03:49.078
farmers, they didn't raise dogs like sugar cane.

03:50.898 --> 03:54.963
After the cane went out, well, then of course they 
went to cotton over there. The prairie farm went to

03:54.983 --> 03:57.106
cotton, too. But I don't know. It just seemed like 
the cotton farming, that is, these big farmers,

04:00.950 --> 04:10.622
they just gradually went down.

04:13.305 --> 04:19.453
There's more cotton farmers out on the prairie out 
here in recent years than anywhere. You're

04:21.239 --> 04:22.321
talking about oil. What is the booths on all of 
them? They own most of the oil at Thompson or who

04:26.226 --> 04:28.650
does? No, I wouldn't say. He said your oil. The 
Moore family that I'm talking about, different

04:34.940 --> 04:39.306
people here in Richmond had a lot of land. Now they 
have sulfur and oil. And the Goobles is down at

04:43.753 --> 04:47.478
Thompson. That's Burke Goobles and all of them? 
That's his folks, his ancestors, his folks. And

04:54.273 --> 04:57.897
Big Creek Oil Field, there's a lot of that. The A.P. 
George family had a lot. They were big branches and

05:02.081 --> 05:04.864
farmers. Big Creek Oil Field, practically all of 
it was on Bud Davis' ranch, and he was a brother of

05:04.884 --> 05:14.295
Mrs. A.P. George. Bud died while she inherited 
that. But the big Greek oil field was a sort of a

05:21.331 --> 05:29.900
minor operation for a good many years. They just, 
oh, here in the last several years, they've

05:30.801 --> 05:43.854
drilled wells out there and made lots of wells on 
that Davis Ranch. OK, how did Miss Agnes Booth, you

05:44.375 --> 05:48.199
know, like, there's, who, Who's her ancestors? Is 
she a George way back? No, no.

05:56.474 --> 05:57.876
Her husband had the money. She didn't have it. She 
married money. Mr. Tom Booth had the money.

