07:10.673 --> 07:13.796
Derricks and the R.M.N., right? That's when I 
started to have Wooden Derricks. Wooden derrick

07:19.507 --> 07:23.132
was pretty handy on cold nights. Cold nights in 
that derrick. Wooden derrick legs, all of that.

07:31.425 --> 07:45.306
Come out about so far each way from the corner of the 
derrick, you could back up in there and get out of

07:31.425 --> 07:45.306
that

07:31.425 --> 07:45.306
cold wind. Have you always been in the oil field? 
Since you've been here in Richmond? Well... I

07:50.900 --> 07:52.081
mean, most of the time. Practically most of the 
time. I pulled around both filling stations once

07:54.304 --> 08:00.192
and got out for a while.

08:06.741 --> 08:10.045
The only way I've ever been able to make a living, 
though, off of you. Yeah.

08:16.662 --> 08:20.186
He liked it, that's the way it goes. Yeah, I know, 
sir. I started rough-necking at that big creek. In

08:25.071 --> 08:27.774
fact, the first job I ever had was to find a boiler. 
Not a boiler, an A-boiler. A small one, at that. You

08:34.902 --> 08:35.783
worked the boiler? You were, well, actually a 
motorman, right? Huh? Farmer. Farmer? Oh. Well,

08:41.029 --> 08:45.994
there was an old man by the name of Rich. He promoted 
money to the River Wildcat down there across the

08:47.999 --> 08:58.314
creek from Big Creek off me. And he got down, oh, 
about 2,500 feet and had some six-inch casings set

08:58.334 --> 09:10.171
and run out of money.

09:12.895 --> 09:15.559
And he hired me to drive while he was rigged. So I was 
out there laying around watching that rig. Wasn't

09:22.721 --> 09:26.106
there a way for anybody to get in there and get him? 
There ain't anyone that's walked.

09:32.114 --> 09:35.219
So he got a little more money together. The driller 
come out there with a dead man and two roughnecks.

09:40.506 --> 09:45.613
Told me he was a father and mother of a mother's 
wife. He said, Father Boyle, you had your driver

09:46.420 --> 09:54.031
watching you, the farmer.

09:55.493 --> 10:06.469
With a little instruction from some of these 
roughnecks, I learned what to do to get some steam

09:55.493 --> 10:06.469
up. So I was a farmer.

10:10.675 --> 10:11.736
Fired with oil.

10:16.728 --> 10:22.714
Yeah, that's where I started.

10:22.734 --> 10:34.086
And then after he run out of money, then again, then 
I went to work in the Gulf out there, roughly. Gulf

10:34.106 --> 10:34.907
oil company? Mm-hmm. Who owns most of the wells 
down there? Isn't it Humboldt? Or Walexone? In Big

10:43.516 --> 10:44.237
Creek? Well, in Thompson and Big Creek. Well, in 
Big Creek, the Gulf Company got practically

10:47.053 --> 10:54.081
everything out there. Thompson and Gulf and 
Humboldt.

11:00.769 --> 11:03.552
How about Orchard, Joe? How about Orchard? Well, 
Gulf got the biggest part of that. Sulphur, too?

11:11.662 --> 11:12.823
Well, the... No, what's the name of that sulfur 
company? The plant now is shut down. They're

11:20.882 --> 11:24.986
getting all that sulfur out there in West Texas 
now. But, oh, shucks, what's the name of that

11:26.748 --> 11:31.814
sulfur company? Duval. Duval, yeah. When did they 
start, you know, drilling down here at Thompson?

11:38.302 --> 11:44.329
Thompson, they discovered, well, Thompson came 
in in 1932.

